    <h3 id="asio">Ableton Live &amp; ASIO</h3>
    <p><strong>OVERVIEW</strong> — The UltraLite-mk3 includes an ASIO driver that provides multi-channel I/O and sample-accurate synchronization for ASIO-compatible hosts.</p>
    <p><strong>What is ASIO?</strong> ASIO stands for Audio Streaming Input and Output.</p>
    <p>In Ableton Live, open <strong>Preferences → Audio</strong>. Choose <strong>ASIO</strong> as the Driver Type and select <strong>MOTU Audio ASIO</strong> as the Audio Device. Use the Input Config and Output Config buttons to enable channels, and use the Hardware Setup button to open MOTU Audio Console.</p>
    <p>Before running Ableton Live, launch MOTU Audio Console to enable desired hardware inputs/outputs — only enabled I/O will be available to the host.</p>

    <h4>Reducing monitoring latency</h4>
    <p><strong>Samples Per Buffer</strong> — The Samples Per Buffer setting can be used to reduce the delay — or monitoring latency — that you hear when live audio is patched through your UltraLite-mk3 hardware and Ableton Live. For example, live instruments patched through the UltraLite-mk3 and monitored in Live may require lower buffer sizes. See chapter 9, “Reducing Monitoring Latency” for complete details.</p>

    <h4>Direct monitoring</h4>
    <p>The Direct Monitoring option allows you to monitor inputs directly in the UltraLite-mk3 hardware with near zero latency and no drain on the computer. When enabled, Ableton Live will use the UltraLite-mk3’s CueMix FX monitoring features whenever you use Live’s monitoring features.</p>

